<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Definition List of Web Development Terms</title>
  <style>
    body {
      font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif;
      background-color: #f4f4f4;
      color: #333;
      padding: 20px;
    }
    h1 {
      text-align: center;
      color: #2b5ca8;
    }
    dl {
      background-color: #fff;
      padding: 20px;
      border-radius: 8px;
      box-shadow: 0 4px 10px rgba(0,0,0,0.1);
      max-width: 700px;
      margin: 20px auto;
    }
    dt {
      font-weight: bold;
      color: #1a3e72;
      margin-top: 10px;
    }
    dd {
      margin-left: 20px;
      margin-bottom: 10px;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>

  <h1>Web Development Terms</h1>

  <dl>
    <dt>HTML (HyperText Markup Language)</dt>
    <dd>It is the standard language used to create and structure the content of web pages. HTML uses tags like &lt;h1&gt;, &lt;p&gt;, &lt;table&gt; to organize information.</dd>

    <dt>CSS (Cascading Style Sheets)</dt>
    <dd>It is used to design and style the web pages created using HTML. CSS controls layout, colors, fonts, and spacing, making web pages look attractive.</dd>

    <dt>JavaScript</dt>
    <dd>A powerful scripting language that allows web pages to become interactive. It can validate forms, create animations, and dynamically change HTML content.</dd>

    <dt>Server</dt>
    <dd>A computer system that stores, processes, and delivers web pages to users through the internet. Examples include Apache, Nginx, and Node.js servers.</dd>

    <dt>Browser</dt>
    <dd>A software application that displays web pages. It interprets HTML, CSS, and JavaScript to show the final website. Examples: Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge.</dd>

    <dt>Database</dt>
    <dd>It stores and manages website data such as user information or content. Examples include MySQL, MongoDB, and PostgreSQL.</dd>
  </dl>

</body>
  </html>
